    en: "Ice dams form when heat escapes through the roof, melts snow, and the water refreezes at the cold edge. The ice backs up under the shingles and water leaks into the house. For a homeowner, standard homeowner's insurance usually covers the interior water damage but not the ice dam removal or the roof repair itself. For a tenant, an ice dam that leaks is a habitability problem; the landlord has to fix the roof and the interior damage. The long-term fix is proper attic insulation and ventilation. The legal framework mixes common-law premises liability, the statutory warranty of habitability (RPL 235-b), and insurance contract law."
